Reminder:

School will begin face to face tomorrow at 10:30! We are excited to see our students! Bus changes cannot be made anymore this evening. Any bus changes made tonight will be reflected on Thursday's run.

School will be face to face on Tuesday and Thursday for the first two weeks. Wednesdays are virtual learning days for all students. No school on Monday or Friday for the first two weeks.

Remote learners - You can pick up your Chromebook and schedule on Wednesday after 1:00 at the school. We will provide meals to our remote learners every Wednesday. If you would like meals this week, please call the school to get on the list before noon tomorrow, Tuesday, 8/25. Any calls after that will be on next Wednesday's list. Wednesday meal pick ups will include five breakfasts and five lunches.

Have a great evening!

E-TC Fall Sports

Students interested in participating in any athletics can get a physical at the Ontonagon Clinic for $5.00. This money will be donated back to the Booster Club. If you had a physical last year and you have no current health concerns, you can complete a questionnaire online at mhsaa.com or pick up a form from the school or Dave Besonen, AD.

6-12 grade Cross Country will hold its first practice on Wednesday, August 12th at 9:00 am. Please meet in the bleachers on the north side of the football field.

JV & Varsity Volleyball will hold their first practice on Wednesday, August 12th from 10:00 am-11:30 am. Please meet in the bleachers on the south side of the football field. Practice will be outdoors.

post_text:
The Ewen-Trout Creek School District values your children, your families, and our staff. We have established a "Return to School" committee comprised of board members, teachers, administrators, maintenance personnel, bus driver, and parents. We are working on our "Return to School" plan to come up with the safest way to bring our students back this fall. This plan will include a virtual/ remote learning option for families with health concerns.

As long as we are in Phase 4 or 5 of the Michigan's Reopening Plan, E-TC will open on August 25th! We miss our students and look forward to seeing them soon! More information will be coming as our plan is finalized. Please message us with any specific questions or concerns.

DAIRY BOXES ARE HERE! When you arrive, drive around the school to the southeast corner, near the gym and the custodian's room. A volunteer will bring a box to you.

We will be here until 3:00 today. If you miss that time, you may come during meal pick up tomorrow (Tuesday, June 30th) from 10:00 - 2:00 until they run out. If you are signed up for meal pick up you will automatically receive a dairy box.

Each box will contain: white milk, strawberry milk, chocolate milk, sour cream, cottage cheese, cream cheese and french onion chip dip.

The boxes are free, available to ANYONE in the community, and will be distributed on a first come first serve basis.

post_text:
Congratulations to freshman Hazel Strong for being nominated as E-TC Student of the Month!

Hazel is involved in band, football, and baseball. She helps friends and peers with homework outside of school, has volunteered at a local pasty sale, and works at a local gift shop. Hazel enjoys skiing, swimming, biking, spending time in the sun,and chemistry. She loves smoothies, football, baseball, and mowing the lawn. Hazel has expressed interest in becoming a chemist or working with chemistry in some capacity. She also wants to open her own smoothie shop someday. Hazel is the daughter of Ted and Michelle Strong of Trout Creek.

According to E-TC math teacher, Branden Broniewicz, Hazel works hard on all of her classwork. On top of that, she is willing to help others understand what is going on, inside and outside of her classes. During the school shut down, she has been trying to get her peers to attend the Google Meetings and helping her siblings when she can. She will even read the daily math pun to her mom everyday for a chuckle.

Keep up the great work, Hazel!

Ewen-Trout Creek School District added 4 new photos.
May 26 at 10:01 AM ·

E-TC came together today to celebrate our graduating class with a parade. Teachers, retired teachers, paraprofessionals, school board members, the school liaison officer, the secretary, and administrators practiced social distancing while visiting all 23 seniors' homes on a 138 mile loop around the county. A mini marching band was on hand to play the school song for each student. Graduates were left with a "Graduate" sign and a bag of goodies.

We have missed our students tremendously and it was wonderful to see them. We are proud of the Class of 2020!

The Commencement ceremony has been rescheduled for Friday, July 10th, 2020. Details will be announced closer to that date.

#PantherPride #Classof2020 #ETCPanthers

post_text:
The May Mental Health Awareness Team would like to invite you to participate in a challenge to end stigma and raise awareness about mental health. Students from Ontonagon and Ewen-Trout Creek and members of Ontonagon Communities that Care, GOISD, Western UP Health Department, Ontonagon Suicide Prevention Coalition and Copper Country Community Mental Health have put together this video.

We invite you to upload photos, artwork, creatively made videos, whatever you feel will inspire others on these Facebook pages. You are also invited to use the hashtags #gogreenformentalhealth #endstigma #maymentalhealthawareness to help spread the word on Instagram.

Randomly selected posts will be chosen for gift cards. Winners will be announced on May 18th.
Please be respectful with your entries, but please have fun.
From all of our team, Thank you.

E-TC Families, please watch the mail for a P-EBT card. These are coming from the state. If you have questions, please contact 1-833-905-0028.

P-EBT Food Assistance Benefits for Families -

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer Program (P-EBT) food assistance benefits will go to Michigan families with students ages 0-26 that are eligible for Free or Reduced-Price School Meals.

If the student is eligible based on a Free or Reduced-Price Meal the pre-loaded P-EBT card will come in the mail and will be in the oldest school aged child’s name, not the parents name.

https://www.michigan.gov/mde/0,4615,7-140-66254_99536---,00.html

Today is National Kindergarten Day. In this video, Miss Kaitlin combined counting and exercise with our kindergarten students.

Physical activity has a positive effect on the brain. The flow of oxygen to the brain is increased. The number of brain neurotransmitters is increased, which assists your ability to focus, concentrate, learn, remember and handle stress.

What are you doing to stay active today?

post_text:
If you need internet service, please call Spectrum/Charter at the number below. They can determine if it is available at your address. If so, it will be provided free of charge for two months.

COVID-19 Remote Education Credit

During this time of uncertainty due to COVID-19, our customers need to stay connected more than ever.

We’re committed to offering special discounts to households affected by this virus. Beginning Monday, March 16, we’ll offer free access to internet and WiFi for 60-days for new Pre-K to 12, college student and teacher households who don't currently have internet or WiFi service. This discount will be applied as a credit for your first two months of internet services. We’ll waive any installation or pre-payment fees to help get you started.

You can qualify for this offer if you:

Have a student of qualifying age at your service address with remote education needs
Have not subscribed to our internet services within the past 30 days
Call (855) 243-8892 to sign up for this offer.

post_text:
E-TC will be providing free meals to any child 18 and under.
Beginning on Tuesday, April 14th, bags with 5 breakfasts & 5 lunches will be available for curbside pickup between 11:00 a.m. and 2:00 p.m.

Families wishing to be put on the list for meals should call 906-813-0620, Option 1, by noon on Friday, April 10th. Once you get on the list, you do not have to call again.

Families can drive up to the curb by the main door. You can signal how many children you need meals for and someone will bring the bags out. You should not get out of the car.

If you cannot pick up the meals, other arrangements can be made. Please notify Pam at the phone number listed.

Additionally, school schedules are being established and you will hear from your child's teacher/s very soon, if you haven't already. Continue to have your child check their email.

We really miss our students.

post_text:
According to the Governor's executive order, students are not allowed in the school until after June 30th. Our education will continue through alternate methods. Many students have already been engaged in learning opportunities through their class page, Class Dojo, or Google Classroom.

7th - 12th grade students, please make sure you check your school email daily. If you cannot remember your log in please call the school or email Pam at besonenp@etc.k12.mi.us. You can expect to hear from your teachers next week.

We will have students' belongings and school work available for you to pick up soon. Please watch for announcements.

We are also working on plans to celebrate our seniors' accomplisments at a graduation ceremony after June 30th. We are making arrangements for other special school events to occur this summer. We are determined to make the best of this school year for our students! We miss you! Stay healthy!

Wash your hands frequently, cough into your sleeve, avoid touching your face, and sanitize frequently touched surfaces.

Congratulations to junior Abbie LeGault for being named Student of the Month.

Abbie is the daughter of Stosha Pole and Tommy LeGault. She is involved in basketball and volleyball as well as being a Student Council Class Representative. "While playing basketball, I enjoy working with my teammates. We are like a family. I like art and being creative with still life using watercolors, and hanging out with my friends. I plan to go to Northern Michigan University and become a chiropractor."

Abbie was nominated by Ms. Tammy Lancioni, Spanish teacher. Abbie is always prepared for class. She is pleasant and she participates without being called upon. She pays attention to what’s being taught.

Great work, Abbie!

#Pantherpride

The School Success Program held a "Would you be my Valentine?” perfect attendance class challenge for kindergarten through sixth grade. Congratulations second and fourth grade for winning the challenge! Second and fourth grade celebrated with ice cream floats and prizes.

Why does attendance matter?
*Good attendance matters for school success, starting as early as prekindergarten and throughout elementary school, and helps students stay on the path to academic success. By middle and high school, poor attendance is a leading indicator of dropout. Absences represent lost opportunities to learn in the classroom.

We started this year's 6th grade outdoor education program with snowmobile safety. We collaborate with the Ontonagon Sheriff's Dept., the USFS, the DNR (Department of Natural Resources), and GLIFWC (Great Lakes Indian Fish & Wildlife Commission) to provide the classroom education and the practical experience. Each student leaves with a snowmobile safety certificate after successful completion of the course.

We were happy to see two E-TC graduates, Aaron Schneider, helping with the program as a DNR Porcupine Mountain State Park Ranger and Josh Lopac, USFS LEO.

The TRIO Talent Search brought area TRIO TS 9th grade students to the Robotics & STEM Day on Tuesday, January 28 at E-TC.

LEXUL taught the students how to code robots to move forward, pick up a ball and move it to a higher shelf. If coded correctly, the robot would be able to do this task in one fluid movement, without having to intervene to correct the robot.

Congratulations to 10th grader, Sierra Endel, for being named the “Student of the Month”! Sierra is involved in choir and interested in dog training.

“I am inspired to work hard and achieve knowledge from the classes I participate in. Knowledge is something no one can take away from you and you’ll have that the rest of your life. My other interests are hunting, fishing, dog training, and sketching still animals.”

Sierra plans to double major in Entrepreneurship and dog training/animal psychology.

According to Ms. Tammy Lancioni, Spanish teacher, Sierra is always prepared for class. She is pleasant and she participates without being called upon. She’s motivated to achieve and accomplish.

Keep up the great work, Sierra!

Our Robotics program is up and running under the leadership of Mr. Ted Trudgeon. Mr. and Mrs. Alinen have provided great parent leadership as well.

The team will be competing in two events this year, one being farther than in the past. To help with the cost of the registration fees, the base robot kit, motels and travel, they were supported by the last “Quarters for a Cause” event. Thank you all for your support at "Quarters for a Cause"!

They will also be having a pasty sale on March 21st. Anyone wanting to donate their time and/or order pasties can contact Colleen Nelson at 906-250-8930. If you would like to donate to the Robotics program or have questions about it you can contact Robin Alinen on Facebook or call at 906-235-2743.

post_text: Another successful year collecting for the TV6 Canathon Drive. The support we receive from our community is amazing! A total of 728 lbs was collected! The 1st/2nd & 8th grade students won the competition for bringing in the most non-perishable items. Thanks to the 4th & 5th grades for weighing & totaling the items. They'll all be receiving an ice cream treat! Thanks to Bob Neumann, the food pantry coordinator, & our volunteers for bringing the items to the food pantry!
